<article>
    <h1>MOH re&#xAD;view&#xAD;ing fund&#xAD;ing sup&#xAD;port for screen&#xAD;ing</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201225/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-25"><time>2020-12-25</time></a>
        - <span>SINGAPORE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Amelia Teng</span>
    </section>

    <p>The Min­istry of Health (MOH) told The Straits Times it is re­view­ing the fund­ing sup­port for pre-im­plan­ta­tion ge­netic di­ag­no­sis (PGD) and pre-im­plan­ta­tion ge­netic screen­ing (PGS), and will re­lease de­tails when ready.</p>
    <p>It added that the Gov­ern­ment will con­tinue to en­sure the ac­ces­si­bil­ity and af­ford­abil­ity of such ser­vices for Sin­ga­pore­ans.</p>
    <p>PGS is dif­fer­ent from PGD in that it screens for the cor­rect num­ber of chro­mo­somes in­stead of known hered­i­tary dis­eases.</p>
    <p>The PGS ser­vice was rolled out in 2017 as a pilot, but is now be­ing ex­tended to more pa­tients. It will re­main ac­ces­si­ble to el­i­gi­ble pa­tients un­til the full re­view is com­plete, said the MOH spokesman. She added that de­mand for PGD has been “sta­ble over the years”.</p>
    <p>Dr Serene Lim, con­sul­tant at Sin­ga­pore Gen­eral Hospi­tal’s De­part­ment of Ob­stet­rics & Gy­nae­col­ogy, said it has seen one to two cases on av­er­age yearly for PGD.</p>
    <p>She noted there is greater aware­ness among cou­ples to screen for ge­netic dis­eases. The most com­mon con­di­tions at her cen­tre are the blood dis­or­der tha­las­saemia, and chro­mo­so­mal translo­ca­tion.</p>
    <p>Dr Jessie Phoon, di­rec­tor and se­nior con­sul­tant of KKIVF Cen­tre at KK Women’s and Chil­dren’s Hospi­tal, said it has done about six PGD biop­sies a year in the past five years.</p>
    <p>Thom­son Fer­til­ity Cen­tre car­ries out about three to four such pro­cesses yearly.</p>
    <p>In a joint re­ply, the cen­tre’s med­i­cal di­rec­tor Loh Seong Feei and chief em­bry­ol­o­gist Ethi­raj Balaji Prasath, said: “PGD is gen­er­ally re­quested by those with known ge­netic dis­eases and those with re­peated mis­car­riages be­cause of ge­netic rea­sons.”</p>


</article>

